      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Certainly! Proponents of strict border security and immigration enforcement often argue from the standpoint of labor market integrity and economic sovereignism to contend that such measures protect the domestic workforce and preserve wage stability. Advocates for this perspective contend that the unrestricted entry of immigrant labor can create downward pressures on wages by increasing labor supply, particularly in low-skill sectors where immigrants might be willing to accept lower wages. They argue that this can lead to wage suppression and depressed salary levels for domestic workers, thus creating unfair competition within the labor market. Furthermore, proponents highlight that when labor markets are flooded with anomalously low wage labor, it can create an economically distorted environment that undermines job opportunities and demand for domestic labor, effectively destabilizing the labor market equilibrium.\n\nEconomically, they often present fertile ground for the development of wage dumping strategies, where companies could exploit a weak or saturated labor market to maximize profits at the expense of fair labor compensation. This, in turn, can result in a loss of purchasing power for domestic workers and create pockets of economic disaffection that might not be able to be reflected in traditional economic indicators due to the informal nature and subterranean labor engagements that can emerge.\n\nMoreover, advocates point out that protections for domestic workers need to be enforced to maintain",
